	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The Write tool is repeatedly blocked on permission approval. The research has been fully gathered. Here is a summary of all findings:\n\n---\n\n## EU AI Policy & Legislative Developments — Feb–March 2026\n\n### 1. Council Agrees Digital Omnibus on AI Position — March 13, 2026\nThe EU Council agreed its negotiating mandate on the \"Digital Omnibus on AI\" (Omnibus VII). Key changes: extended compliance deadlines for high-risk AI systems (Annex III to Dec 2, 2027; Annex I to Aug 2, 2028 — up to 16 months additional runway), SME exemptions extended to small mid-caps (<500 employees), and reinforced AI Office enforcement powers. Source: consilium.europa.eu\n\n### 2. EP Committees Vote on AI Omnibus — March 18, 2026\nIMCO and LIBE committees adopted report A10-0073/2026 (101–9–8). MEPs added: AI watermarking deadline accelerated to Nov 2, 2026 (Commission had proposed Feb 2027); explicit ban on \"nudifier\" deepfake applications creating non-consensual intimate imagery. Plenary vote expected March 26, then Council-Parliament trilogue begins. Source: europarl.europa.eu, iapp.org\n\n### 3. Aug 2, 2026 Enforcement Baseline Still Applies\nAbsent Omnibus enactment, the original full-applicability date stands with fines up to €35M/7% global turnover. First harmonized AI standard (prEN 18286, QMS for AI Act) entered CEN/CENELEC public enquiry on Oct 30, 2025. Source: ec.europa.eu, sombrainc.com\n\n### 4. Academic Analysis: Paradoxes of EU AI Regulation — March 10, 2026\nPeer-reviewed critique identifies: (1) rights-first framework vs. competitiveness paradox; (2) complexity paradox from 1,000+ provisions; (3) rule-of-law concerns over Omnibus timing. Source: theregreview.org\n\n### 5. Big Tech Lobbying Critique — January 14, 2026\nCorporate Europe Observatory documents Big Tech Brussels lobbying up 33.6% to €151M (2025). Commission language mirrors DigitalEurope/Google/Meta requests verbatim in multiple AI Act rollbacks. Source: corporateeurope.org\n\n### 6. International Governance — Q1 2026\nEU to endorse AI Impact Summit 2026 declaration (New Delhi). EuroStack partnerships with Brazil, Chile, South Korea, Taiwan, Canada, Japan on sovereign AI infrastructure. Source: euronews.com, iapp.org\n\n### 7. K&L Gates Legal Alert — January 20, 2026\nAdvises companies not to pause compliance work awaiting Omnibus; Aug 2026 deadlines operative until formal enactment. Source: klgates.com\n\n---\n\nThe file write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md` is being blocked by permission prompts requiring user approval. Please grant write permission to that path so the file can be saved, or let me know an alternative location." ;
