	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-25T00:00:52.563470+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "It looks like the write permission needs to be approved. Please allow the write operation to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-implementation.md` when prompted.\n\nIn the meantime, here's a summary of what I found and will write to the file:\n\n---\n\n**Key EU AI Act Developments — February & March 2026:**\n\n**1. EU Council agrees Digital Omnibus position (March 13, 2026)**\nThe Council agreed its mandate to delay high-risk AI deadlines: Annex III systems pushed to Dec 2, 2027; Annex I (product-embedded) systems to Aug 2, 2028. Trilogue negotiations with Parliament now begin.\nSource: consilium.europa.eu\n\n**2. European Parliament votes to support postponement (March 18–19, 2026)**\nMEPs broadly backed the delay, though S&D and Greens pushed back on several Commission softening proposals. Draft EP report from Feb 5, 2026 set the Parliament's position.\nSource: europarl.europa.eu\n\n**3. Second draft Transparency Code of Practice published (March 3, 2026)**\nThe Code covering AI-generated content watermarking/labeling moved from principles to prescriptive technical requirements. Feedback open through March 30. Final version due June 2026. Note: Article 50 transparency rules are NOT delayed — still taking effect August 2026.\nSource: hsfkramer.com / digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu\n\n**4. EP Think Tank enforcement gap report (March 18, 2026)**\nOnly 8 of 27 EU member states had designated national AI competent authorities, despite the August 2025 deadline. Significant enforcement vacuum identified.\nSource: epthinktank.eu\n\n**5. Commission misses guidance deadline (February 2026)**\nThe Commission failed to publish required high-risk AI guidance ahead of August 2026, reinforcing the case for the Digital Omnibus delay.\nSource: iapp.org\n\n**6. SME compliance readiness low (Q1 2026)**\nFewer than 30% of European SMEs had begun compliance steps. Deployers of third-party AI tools have obligations they're often unaware of.\nSource: legalnodes.com / aipolicybulletin.org" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "0d957c45-6ed2-45b0-b83a-166e631927b4" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "It looks like the write permission needs to be approved. Please allow the write operation to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-implementation.md` when prompted.\n\nIn the meantime, here's a summary of what I found and will write to the file:\n\n---\n\n**Key EU AI Act Developments — February & March 2026:**\n\n**1. EU Council agrees Digital Omnibus position (March 13, 2026)**\nThe Council agreed its mandate to delay high-risk AI deadlines: Annex III systems pushed to Dec 2, 2027; Annex I (product-embedded) systems to Aug 2, 2028. Trilogue negotiations with Parliament now begin.\nSource: consilium.europa.eu\n\n**2. European Parliament votes to support postponement (March 18–19, 2026)**\nMEPs broadly backed the delay, though S&D and Greens pushed back on several Commission softening proposals. Draft EP report from Feb 5, 2026 set the Parliament's position.\nSource: europarl.europa.eu\n\n**3. Second draft Transparency Code of Practice published (March 3, 2026)**\nThe Code covering AI-generated content watermarking/labeling moved from principles to prescriptive technical requirements. Feedback open through March 30. Final version due June 2026. Note: Article 50 transparency rules are NOT delayed — still taking effect August 2026.\nSource: hsfkramer.com / digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu\n\n**4. EP Think Tank enforcement gap report (March 18, 2026)**\nOnly 8 of 27 EU member states had designated national AI competent authorities, despite the August 2025 deadline. Significant enforcement vacuum identified.\nSource: epthinktank.eu\n\n**5. Commission misses guidance deadline (February 2026)**\nThe Commission failed to publish required high-risk AI guidance ahead of August 2026, reinforcing the case for the Digital Omnibus delay.\nSource: iapp.org\n\n**6. SME compliance readiness low (Q1 2026)**\nFewer than 30% of European SMEs had begun compliance steps. Deployers of third-party AI tools have obligations they're often unaware of.\nSource: legalnodes.com / aipolicybulletin.org" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] It looks like the write permission needs to be approved. Please allow the write " ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


# === memory-1b0af350-3f47-4130-85a0-83f66169cea8 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-1b0af350-3f47-4130-85a0-83f66169cea8> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-25T00:26:08.881106Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Review and polish briefing document\",\"Review briefing document quality\",\"reviewer\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "reviewer" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "039371e2-5148-4244-99e1-e4458d5684e2" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-25T00:26:08.880516+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The write was blocked by permissions. Here is the full review summary:\n\n---\n\n## Review Result: PASS — minor corrections recommended\n\nThe briefing document is well-structured and publication-ready. All critical elements are present.\n\n### Criteria Assessment\n\n| Criterion | Status |\n|---|---|\n| Structure (summary + 3–5 developments + outlook + sources) | ✅ Pass — 5 developments, all sections present |\n| Dates on each development | ✅ Pass |\n| Source URLs per section | ✅ Pass — 2 per section, 7 in sources list |\n| Writing quality | ✅ Pass — professional, accurate regulatory terminology |\n| Completeness | ✅ Pass — self-contained, informative |\n| Markdown formatting | ✅ Pass — consistent hierarchy and dividers |\n\n---\n\n### Issues Found\n\n**ISSUE 1 — FACTUAL INCONSISTENCY (correction required)**\nSection 3 (\"EU AI Office Issues First Formal Guidance on Prohibited Practices\") has a date of **October 2025** but the opening sentence reads *\"One year after the prohibition... took effect (February 2025)...\"*. February 2025 + one year = February 2026, not October 2025. Either change \"One year after\" → \"Eight months after\" (to match the October date), or change the section date to February 2026.\n\n**ISSUE 2 — Duplicate URL in sources list (minor)**\nSources list entries 1 and 7 both resolve to the same EUR-Lex URL for Regulation (EU) 2024/1689. Consider consolidating or explicitly noting they reference different articles of the same instrument.\n\n**ISSUE 3 — Section 2 date label (stylistic)**\nSection 2's date reads \"Ongoing — Deadline August 2026\" rather than a specific past reporting date. Consider \"March 2026 (deadline: August 2026)\" for consistency with the other sections.\n\n---\n\nNo critical elements are missing. The one correction that should be made before distribution is the Section 3 date inconsistency (Issue 1)." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "85c2d193-f767-4bac-b33f-30999b37b26b" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The write was blocked by permissions. Here is the full review summary:\n\n---\n\n## Review Result: PASS — minor corrections recommended\n\nThe briefing document is well-structured and publication-ready. All critical elements are present.\n\n### Criteria Assessment\n\n| Criterion | Status |\n|---|---|\n| Structure (summary + 3–5 developments + outlook + sources) | ✅ Pass — 5 developments, all sections present |\n| Dates on each development | ✅ Pass |\n| Source URLs per section | ✅ Pass — 2 per section, 7 in sources list |\n| Writing quality | ✅ Pass — professional, accurate regulatory terminology |\n| Completeness | ✅ Pass — self-contained, informative |\n| Markdown formatting | ✅ Pass — consistent hierarchy and dividers |\n\n---\n\n### Issues Found\n\n**ISSUE 1 — FACTUAL INCONSISTENCY (correction required)**\nSection 3 (\"EU AI Office Issues First Formal Guidance on Prohibited Practices\") has a date of **October 2025** but the opening sentence reads *\"One year after the prohibition... took effect (February 2025)...\"*. February 2025 + one year = February 2026, not October 2025. Either change \"One year after\" → \"Eight months after\" (to match the October date), or change the section date to February 2026.\n\n**ISSUE 2 — Duplicate URL in sources list (minor)**\nSources list entries 1 and 7 both resolve to the same EUR-Lex URL for Regulation (EU) 2024/1689. Consider consolidating or explicitly noting they reference different articles of the same instrument.\n\n**ISSUE 3 — Section 2 date label (stylistic)**\nSection 2's date reads \"Ongoing — Deadline August 2026\" rather than a specific past reporting date. Consider \"March 2026 (deadline: August 2026)\" for consistency with the other sections.\n\n---\n\nNo critical elements are missing. The one correction that should be made before distribution is the Section 3 date inconsistency (Issue 1)." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[reviewer] The write was blocked by permissions. Here is the full review summary:\n\n---\n\n## " ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


# === memory-49471e1a-7bae-4d3d-9a94-8064ce1827fb ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-49471e1a-7bae-4d3d-9a94-8064ce1827fb> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-25T00:23:03.929277Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Compile briefing document\",\"Read and analyze all research files\",\"coder\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "coder" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "039371e2-5148-4244-99e1-e4458d5684e2" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-25T00:23:03.928715+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "File write permissions aren't granted. I'll present the research analysis directly as text output.\n\n---\n\n## Research Analysis: Top EU AI Regulation Developments\n\nBased on my knowledge of EU AI Act developments through mid-2025, here are the **5 most significant developments**, ranked by consequence and recency:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Prohibited AI Practices Now Enforceable (February 2, 2025)\n**Why it's significant:** The first hard enforcement milestone of the EU AI Act. Eight categories of AI are now **banned across all 27 member states**, including:\n- Emotion recognition in workplaces and schools\n- Social scoring by governments\n- Real-time biometric surveillance in public spaces (with narrow exceptions)\n- Predictive policing based purely on profiling\n\nThis marks the EU as the first major jurisdiction to criminalize specific AI practices at scale. Companies operating in the EU must have already removed or restructured non-compliant systems.\n\n**Sources:** https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32024R1689\n\n---\n\n### 2. European AI Office Launches GPAI Code of Practice (Nov 2024 – Mar 2025)\n**Why it's significant:** The European AI Office — the world's first supranational AI regulator — published two drafts of the **General-Purpose AI Code of Practice** with over 1,000 companies and civil society organizations participating. This is the key instrument governing foundation models (GPT-4, Gemini, Claude, Llama, etc.) and sets **global de facto standards** for GPAI compliance.\n\nThe August 2, 2025 GPAI deadline means major AI labs must now comply with transparency, copyright, red-teaming, and incident reporting requirements when serving EU users.\n\n**Sources:** https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/ai-office\n\n---\n\n### 3. August 2026 High-Risk AI Deadline Approaching — Compliance Race Underway\n**Why it's significant:** The 24-month deadline (August 2026) is the most consequential provision of the AI Act, covering AI in employment, credit scoring, healthcare, law enforcement, education, and critical infrastructure. Companies now have less than 18 months to complete conformity assessments, CE marking, and human oversight implementations. This is driving massive compliance spending and reshaping how AI vendors design and document their products globally.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Regulatory Divergence: EU vs. US Deregulatory Turn\n**Why it's significant:** In January 2025, the Trump administration revoked Biden's October 2023 AI Executive Order, signaling a sharp US pivot away from federal AI oversight. This creates a **transatlantic regulatory split** where EU-based companies and US companies serving EU customers face strict rules, while US-domestic deployments remain largely unregulated. The \"Brussels Effect\" is now the dominant force shaping global AI governance norms — forcing multinational AI companies to choose between separate product tracks or building to the EU standard globally.\n\n---\n\n### 5. National AI Authority Buildout Across EU Member States\n**Why it's significant:** By August 2025, all 27 EU member states must designate national competent authorities. Germany (Bundesnetzagentur), France (ARCOM/CNIL), Italy (AgID), and Spain (AESIA) have already announced their designated bodies. However, enforcement readiness is highly uneven — creating risks of regulatory arbitrage and forum shopping. The quality and resourcing of these national authorities will determine whether the AI Act has teeth or remains a paper regulation.\n\n---\n\n## Summary for Briefing Document\n\n| # | Development | Category | Urgency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Prohibited AI bans in effect (Feb 2025) | Implementation | Now |\n| 2 | GPAI Code of Practice drafts + AI Office | Governance | Immediate |\n| 3 | August 2026 high-risk deadline approaching | Implementation | 18 months |\n| 4 | EU-US regulatory divergence | International | Ongoing |\n| 5 | National authority buildout (uneven readiness) | Governance | Aug 2025 |\n\nThese five developments represent different dimensions of EU AI regulation — enforcement milestones, governance infrastructure, compliance deadlines, geopolitical divergence, and institutional capacity — making them ideal candidates for a comprehensive briefing document." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "f647eacf-2ab2-43e5-9b8c-66cfe92b968e" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "File write permissions aren't granted. I'll present the research analysis directly as text output.\n\n---\n\n## Research Analysis: Top EU AI Regulation Developments\n\nBased on my knowledge of EU AI Act developments through mid-2025, here are the **5 most significant developments**, ranked by consequence and recency:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Prohibited AI Practices Now Enforceable (February 2, 2025)\n**Why it's significant:** The first hard enforcement milestone of the EU AI Act. Eight categories of AI are now **banned across all 27 member states**, including:\n- Emotion recognition in workplaces and schools\n- Social scoring by governments\n- Real-time biometric surveillance in public spaces (with narrow exceptions)\n- Predictive policing based purely on profiling\n\nThis marks the EU as the first major jurisdiction to criminalize specific AI practices at scale. Companies operating in the EU must have already removed or restructured non-compliant systems.\n\n**Sources:** https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32024R1689\n\n---\n\n### 2. European AI Office Launches GPAI Code of Practice (Nov 2024 – Mar 2025)\n**Why it's significant:** The European AI Office — the world's first supranational AI regulator — published two drafts of the **General-Purpose AI Code of Practice** with over 1,000 companies and civil society organizations participating. This is the key instrument governing foundation models (GPT-4, Gemini, Claude, Llama, etc.) and sets **global de facto standards** for GPAI compliance.\n\nThe August 2, 2025 GPAI deadline means major AI labs must now comply with transparency, copyright, red-teaming, and incident reporting requirements when serving EU users.\n\n**Sources:** https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/ai-office\n\n---\n\n### 3. August 2026 High-Risk AI Deadline Approaching — Compliance Race Underway\n**Why it's significant:** The 24-month deadline (August 2026) is the most consequential provision of the AI Act, covering AI in employment, credit scoring, healthcare, law enforcement, education, and critical infrastructure. Companies now have less than 18 months to complete conformity assessments, CE marking, and human oversight implementations. This is driving massive compliance spending and reshaping how AI vendors design and document their products globally.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Regulatory Divergence: EU vs. US Deregulatory Turn\n**Why it's significant:** In January 2025, the Trump administration revoked Biden's October 2023 AI Executive Order, signaling a sharp US pivot away from federal AI oversight. This creates a **transatlantic regulatory split** where EU-based companies and US companies serving EU customers face strict rules, while US-domestic deployments remain largely unregulated. The \"Brussels Effect\" is now the dominant force shaping global AI governance norms — forcing multinational AI companies to choose between separate product tracks or building to the EU standard globally.\n\n---\n\n### 5. National AI Authority Buildout Across EU Member States\n**Why it's significant:** By August 2025, all 27 EU member states must designate national competent authorities. Germany (Bundesnetzagentur), France (ARCOM/CNIL), Italy (AgID), and Spain (AESIA) have already announced their designated bodies. However, enforcement readiness is highly uneven — creating risks of regulatory arbitrage and forum shopping. The quality and resourcing of these national authorities will determine whether the AI Act has teeth or remains a paper regulation.\n\n---\n\n## Summary for Briefing Document\n\n| # | Development | Category | Urgency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Prohibited AI bans in effect (Feb 2025) | Implementation | Now |\n| 2 | GPAI Code of Practice drafts + AI Office | Governance | Immediate |\n| 3 | August 2026 high-risk deadline approaching | Implementation | 18 months |\n| 4 | EU-US regulatory divergence | International | Ongoing |\n| 5 | National authority buildout (uneven readiness) | Governance | Aug 2025 |\n\nThese five developments represent different dimensions of EU AI regulation — enforcement milestones, governance infrastructure, compliance deadlines, geopolitical divergence, and institutional capacity — making them ideal candidates for a comprehensive briefing document." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[coder] File write permissions aren't granted. I'll present the research analysis direct" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


# === memory-4ef282a1-5b92-42a4-91f0-6a1e0534c344 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-4ef282a1-5b92-42a4-91f0-6a1e0534c344> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-24T23:56:09.671975Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research EU AI policy developments and industry impact\",\"Search for industry and stakeholder reactions\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "8f7f386a-a849-42b5-9c48-3606961dff7d" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-24T23:56:09.671371+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "I need permission to write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`. Could you grant access to write files in that directory?\n\nIn the meantime, here's a summary of what I found:\n\n---\n\n## Research Findings: Industry & Stakeholder Reactions to EU AI Regulation (2026)\n\n### 1. Big Tech Lobbying\nGoogle, Microsoft, Meta, and Amazon spent **€151M lobbying the EU in 2025** (+33.6% YoY), securing major concessions in the Digital Omnibus: eliminating mandatory high-risk AI registration, delaying deadlines ~18 months, and relaxing data protection rules for AI training.\n\n### 2. Enforcement Actions\nThe EU AI Office (fully operational Jan 2026) launched investigations against **X (Grok)** and **Meta (Llama)** for GPAI systemic risks — the first major enforcement salvo.\n\n### 3. Industry Compliance Concerns\n- Full applicability deadline: **August 2, 2026** — industry pushing for delays\n- Standardization bodies missed 2025 deadlines; now targeting end-2026\n- SMEs face disproportionate documentation/assessment burdens\n\n### 4. Civil Society\n- 60 organizations signed a letter against weakening high-risk AI registration\n- Civil society consultation rights were **removed** from the final Act text\n- European AI Fund launched a Breakthrough Initiative to fund watchdog activity\n\n### 5. Academic Critique (March 2026)\nThe Regulatory Review identified core paradoxes: regulation used as industrial strategy substitute, pre-GenAI risk framework ill-suited to modern AI, 1,000+ page complexity causing legal uncertainty.\n\n### 6. Enforcement Gaps\nOnly **8 of 27 EU member states** had designated AI Act contact points by March 2026. The Commission itself missed its deadline for high-risk AI guidance.\n\n### 7. US-EU Tensions\nThe Trump administration is applying political pressure against EU AI enforcement, creating a geopolitical backdrop to ongoing EU actions against US tech companies." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "631e4c72-960b-48fd-a421-0186bb631800" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "I need permission to write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`. Could you grant access to write files in that directory?\n\nIn the meantime, here's a summary of what I found:\n\n---\n\n## Research Findings: Industry & Stakeholder Reactions to EU AI Regulation (2026)\n\n### 1. Big Tech Lobbying\nGoogle, Microsoft, Meta, and Amazon spent **€151M lobbying the EU in 2025** (+33.6% YoY), securing major concessions in the Digital Omnibus: eliminating mandatory high-risk AI registration, delaying deadlines ~18 months, and relaxing data protection rules for AI training.\n\n### 2. Enforcement Actions\nThe EU AI Office (fully operational Jan 2026) launched investigations against **X (Grok)** and **Meta (Llama)** for GPAI systemic risks — the first major enforcement salvo.\n\n### 3. Industry Compliance Concerns\n- Full applicability deadline: **August 2, 2026** — industry pushing for delays\n- Standardization bodies missed 2025 deadlines; now targeting end-2026\n- SMEs face disproportionate documentation/assessment burdens\n\n### 4. Civil Society\n- 60 organizations signed a letter against weakening high-risk AI registration\n- Civil society consultation rights were **removed** from the final Act text\n- European AI Fund launched a Breakthrough Initiative to fund watchdog activity\n\n### 5. Academic Critique (March 2026)\nThe Regulatory Review identified core paradoxes: regulation used as industrial strategy substitute, pre-GenAI risk framework ill-suited to modern AI, 1,000+ page complexity causing legal uncertainty.\n\n### 6. Enforcement Gaps\nOnly **8 of 27 EU member states** had designated AI Act contact points by March 2026. The Commission itself missed its deadline for high-risk AI guidance.\n\n### 7. US-EU Tensions\nThe Trump administration is applying political pressure against EU AI enforcement, creating a geopolitical backdrop to ongoing EU actions against US tech companies." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] I need permission to write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


