	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-25T00:09:43.044903+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The swarm gate is consistently blocking file writes for this research agent. Here is the complete research output that should be written to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-governance.md`:\n\n---\n\n## Research Findings: EU AI Governance & Policy (February–March 2026)\n\n**7 key developments found:**\n\n---\n\n### 1. EU Council Agrees Negotiating Position on AI Act Streamlining\n**Date:** March 13, 2026\n**Source:** https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2026/03/13/council-agrees-position-to-streamline-rules-on-artificial-intelligence/\n\nThe Council agreed its mandate for the Digital Omnibus VII (AI streamlining) proposal. High-risk AI deadlines are delayed: Annex III stand-alone systems (biometrics, employment, credit) to **2 December 2027**; Annex I AI-in-products to **2 August 2028**. The Council also added a new Article 5 prohibition on AI systems generating non-consensual sexual/intimate imagery, and clarified that national authorities retain jurisdiction over law enforcement, border management, judicial bodies, and financial institutions — even when those systems use GPAI models.\n\nThe mandate is a negotiating position that kicks off trilogue with Parliament and Commission. It does not amend the AI Act itself; the Act remains in force. The clarification on GPAI supervision scope settles months of ambiguity about where EU-level (AI Office) versus national oversight begins.\n\n---\n\n### 2. European Parliament Committees (IMCO/LIBE) Adopt Joint Position\n**Date:** March 18, 2026\n**Source:** https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20260316IPR38219/meps-support-postponement-of-certain-rules-on-artificial-intelligence\n**Additional:** https://www.aiacto.eu/en/blog/vote-imco-libe-digital-omnibus-ai-act-18-mars-2026\n\nVoted 101-9-8 in favour. Parliament agreed on the same delay deadlines as Council (Dec 2027 / Aug 2028) but with **fixed** dates — rejecting the Commission's floating approach. Parliament also moved up the AI-generated content machine-readable marking deadline to **November 2, 2026** (vs. Commission's February 2027). Added: prohibition on \"nudifier\" apps (non-consensual intimate imagery generation), championed by Renew Europe after the Grok/xAI incident. Extended SME reliefs to small mid-caps (under 750 employees / under EUR 150M turnover). Full plenary vote scheduled **March 26, 2026**; trilogue expected April 2026.\n\nThe nudifier ban was not in the Commission proposal. Its addition by Parliament — and parallel addition by Council — means it is very likely to survive trilogue. The earlier AI-content marking deadline (November vs. February) is a key divergence to watch in negotiations.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Second Draft: Code of Practice on AI-Generated Content Transparency\n**Date:** March 5, 2026\n**Source:** https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/code-practice-ai-generated-content\n**Additional:** https://www.hsfkramer.com/notes/ip/2026-03/transparency-obligations-for-ai-generated-content-under-the-eu-ai-act-from-principle-to-practice\n\nThe Commission published the second draft of the Code of Practice on Marking and Labelling of AI-Generated Content (Article 50, AI Act). It covers machine-readable marking of AI-generated audio, image, video, and text. Public feedback window: open until **March 30, 2026**. Final version expected June 2026 before August enforcement date.\n\nThe second draft is significantly more prescriptive than the first — shifting from principles to specific technical commitments on watermarking and provenance tracking. Legal analysts described it as signaling how the AI Office will assess compliance. This code functions as an implementation specification for the Act's transparency obligations and is watched internationally as a potential de facto global standard.\n\n---\n\n### 4. EU Endorses New Delhi Declaration at India AI Impact Summit\n**Date:** February 20, 2026\n**Source:** https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/news/european-union-endorses-leaders-declaration-ai-summit-india\n\nEVP Henna Virkkunen signed the New Delhi Declaration on behalf of the EU at the AI Impact Summit (New Delhi, Feb 18-19), alongside 91 countries. The declaration's seven pillars: human capital, social empowerment, trustworthiness, energy efficiency, science, democratizing AI resources, and economic growth. The EU also launched the **Frontier AI Grand Challenge** (for European AI foundation models) and a **European Legal Gateway Office with India** for standards and digital governance cooperation.\n\nThis was the fifth AI safety summit in the series (Bletchley → Seoul → Paris → New Delhi), and India's first hosting. The EU's endorsement and bilateral India initiatives signaled its push to expand AI governance influence beyond Europe and counter a US-China bilateral framing of global AI governance.\n\n---\n\n### 5. EU AI Office Enters Active GPAI Monitoring Phase\n**Date:** Ongoing / February 2026\n**Source:** https://creati.ai/ai-news/2026-02-12/eu-commission-ai-act-implementation-2026/\n**Additional:** https://axis-intelligence.com/eu-ai-act-news-2026/\n\nWith GPAI obligations in force since August 2025, the AI Office is now in active monitoring mode: reviewing notification compliance for systemic-risk models (threshold: >10^25 FLOP training compute), adversarial testing records, and incident reporting. February 2, 2026 marked the one-year anniversary of Article 5 prohibited practices enforcement, triggering a mandatory Commission review of those prohibitions. Full enforcement powers (fines up to 3% global turnover or EUR 15M) begin August 2, 2026.\n\nReported ongoing investigations include: workplace emotion-recognition systems in multinationals, predictive policing algorithms in EU law enforcement, and biometric categorization in ad-tech — all potential Article 5 violations. No formal enforcement decisions published yet.\n\n---\n\n### 6. CEN-CENELEC: First AI Act Harmonized Standard Enters Public Enquiry\n**Date:** February–March 2026\n**Source:** https://www.complianceweek.com/risk-and-regulatory-compliance/first-standard-for-eu-ai-act-targets-quality-management-regime/36414.article\n**Additional:** https://www.cencenelec.eu/areas-of-work/cen-cenelec-topics/artificial-intelligence/\n\nJTC 21 (300+ experts across 20+ countries) advanced its AI Act standards work. The **Quality Management Systems standard (prEN 18286)** entered Public Enquiry in February 2026 — the first AI Act harmonized standard to reach this stage. Risk management and conformity assessment standards to follow. Target: full package published by Q4 2026 (following October 2025 acceleration decision).\n\nStandards are directly linked to the legislative delay debate: both Parliament and Council cited their absence as justification for pushing back high-risk AI deadlines. These harmonized standards are the legal mechanism enabling \"presumption of conformity\" — without them, providers cannot formally demonstrate compliance even if they meet the Act's requirements. The delay in finalized standards has made JTC 21 politically prominent in the AI Act debate.\n\n---\n\n### 7. AI Act–DSA–DMA–Data Act Regulatory Overlap Intensifies\n**Date:** February 11, 2026 (roundup); March 22, 2026 (follow-up)\n**Source:** https://www.mofo.com/resources/insights/260211-european-digital-compliance-key-digital-regulation\n**Additional:** https://insights.policy-insider.ai/22-03-2026-dsa-enforcement-ai-act-safety-dma-compliance/\n\nMultiple February–March 2026 compliance analyses flagged growing jurisdictional complexity. A single large tech company may simultaneously be a GPAI provider (AI Act), VLOP (DSA), gatekeeper (DMA), and data holder (Data Act) — each framework with different procedural requirements and enforcement bodies. The Commission's January 2026 investigation into Meta's WhatsApp Business API (restricting rival AI providers) implicated both DMA interoperability obligations and AI Act GPAI bundling provisions — raising unresolved questions about which authority leads. DMA formal review due **May 3, 2026**.\n\nThe meta-issue flagged by practitioners: the EU has built a dense digital regulatory stack but has not yet established clear coordination mechanisms between its enforcement bodies. This is expected to become a major policy topic through 2026 as enforcement ramps up across all frameworks simultaneously.\n\n---\n\n### Key Upcoming Dates\n\n| Date | Event |\n|------|-------|\n| March 26, 2026 | EP plenary vote on AI Omnibus amendments |\n| March 30, 2026 | AI-generated content Code of Practice feedback deadline |\n| April 2026 | Trilogue negotiations begin |\n| May 3, 2026 | Commission DMA review deadline |\n| June 2026 | Final AI-generated content Code of Practice |\n| Q4 2026 | CEN-CENELEC harmonized AI standards publication target |\n| August 2, 2026 | Full AI Act enforcement + GPAI fines regime |" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "4db8c717-eeca-4dbb-bb92-3b71768502ca" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The swarm gate is consistently blocking file writes for this research agent. Here is the complete research output that should be written to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-governance.md`:\n\n---\n\n## Research Findings: EU AI Governance & Policy (February–March 2026)\n\n**7 key developments found:**\n\n---\n\n### 1. EU Council Agrees Negotiating Position on AI Act Streamlining\n**Date:** March 13, 2026\n**Source:** https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2026/03/13/council-agrees-position-to-streamline-rules-on-artificial-intelligence/\n\nThe Council agreed its mandate for the Digital Omnibus VII (AI streamlining) proposal. High-risk AI deadlines are delayed: Annex III stand-alone systems (biometrics, employment, credit) to **2 December 2027**; Annex I AI-in-products to **2 August 2028**. The Council also added a new Article 5 prohibition on AI systems generating non-consensual sexual/intimate imagery, and clarified that national authorities retain jurisdiction over law enforcement, border management, judicial bodies, and financial institutions — even when those systems use GPAI models.\n\nThe mandate is a negotiating position that kicks off trilogue with Parliament and Commission. It does not amend the AI Act itself; the Act remains in force. The clarification on GPAI supervision scope settles months of ambiguity about where EU-level (AI Office) versus national oversight begins.\n\n---\n\n### 2. European Parliament Committees (IMCO/LIBE) Adopt Joint Position\n**Date:** March 18, 2026\n**Source:** https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20260316IPR38219/meps-support-postponement-of-certain-rules-on-artificial-intelligence\n**Additional:** https://www.aiacto.eu/en/blog/vote-imco-libe-digital-omnibus-ai-act-18-mars-2026\n\nVoted 101-9-8 in favour. Parliament agreed on the same delay deadlines as Council (Dec 2027 / Aug 2028) but with **fixed** dates — rejecting the Commission's floating